narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: This was a great first rotation that helped me gain my footing and also begin my journey as an independent scientist.
Genetic screens, de novo mutations, autism genetics, some neurodevelopmental analysis, and zebrafish handling/techniques
I learned about cell culture, using r to filter and select data and make graphs, and the basics of epigenetic poising.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: One of the strengths of this lab was the engagement that my PI had with me and also he allowed me to work on many projects and branch out of my previous research.
Strength: freedom to conduct the rotation naturally. Weakness: none

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would, lab rotations are essential for discovering what the lab techniques are like and what the lab culture is like. Imperative for making an assessment of fit for a PhD of >5 years.
Yes. I like being able to try multiple labs before deciding.
